<script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"address":{"addressCountry":"UK","addressLocality":"Wigan","@type":"PostalAddress"},"areaServed":{"@type":"City","name":"Wigan"},"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#org-51ed","geo":{"longitude":-2.6265,"@type":"GeoCoordinates","latitude":53.5457},"url":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/","@type":"LocalBusiness","email":"contact@geotechnical-engineering.biz","name":"Geotechnical Engineering Wigan"},{"areaServed":{"@type":"City","name":"Wigan"},"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#service-51ed","serviceType":"Soil mechanics study","url":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/","@type":"Service","provider":{"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#org-51ed"},"description":"Site-specific soil mechanics study for Wigan. We apply BS 5930 and Eurocode 7 to coal measure drift, glacial till, and made ground. Practical reporting for foundations, retaining walls, and earthworks","name":"Geotechnical Engineering in Wigan"},{"isPartOf":{"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#website-51ed"},"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/","inLanguage":"en","url":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/","@type":"WebPage","name":"Geotechnical Engineering in Wigan"},{"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#website-51ed","inLanguage":"en","url":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/","@type":"WebSite","name":"Wigan"},{"@id":"https://wigan.geotechnical-engineering.biz/#faq-51ed","mainEntity":[{"acceptedAnswer":{"text":"The depth depends on the foundation type and the drift thickness. For a two-storey housing plot we typically go to 8–10 metres to pass through the made ground and into the natural till or bedrock. For larger commercial structures or where deep mine workings are suspected, we can extend boreholes to 25 metres or more. We always check the Coal Authority report before setting the final depth.","@type":"Answer"},"@type":"Question","name":"How deep do you drill for a soil mechanics study in Wigan?"},{"acceptedAnswer":{"text":"A soil mechanics study in Wigan for a residential or light commercial site falls between £2,150 and £3,730. The final figure depends on the number of boreholes, the depth, the laboratory tests required, and whether we need to probe for shallow mine workings. We give a fixed price once we have seen the site layout and the historical records.","@type":"Answer"},"@type":"Question","name":"What is the typical cost range for this study in the Wigan area?"},{"acceptedAnswer":{"text":"We complete the site work and deliver the factual report within two to three weeks for most Wigan projects. If we are running a full lab programme with triaxial and oedometer tests, the interpretive report with foundation recommendations can take an extra week. We keep the timeline tight because we know the contractor is waiting to break ground.","@type":"Answer"},"@type":"Question","name":"How long does it take to get the report after the fieldwork?"},{"acceptedAnswer":{"text":"Yes. That is one of the most common ground conditions we handle in Wigan. We log the spoil, sample it for chemical testing, and assess its compaction and settlement potential. If the spoil is loose or contaminated, we outline options for removal, dynamic compaction, or a suspended floor design. We also check for hidden shafts and vents.","@type":"Answer"},"@type":"Question","name":"Can you investigate a site that has old colliery spoil?"}],"@type":"FAQPage"}]}</script>
